# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cassandra-db
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Avinash Lakshman, a co-author of Amazon's Dynamo, and Prashant Malik developed Cassandra at Facebook to support the inbox search functionality.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Facebook released Cassandra as open-source software on Google Code in July 2008.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] In March 2009, it became an Apache Incubator project and on February 17, 2010, it graduated to a top-level project.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] The developers at Facebook named their database after Cassandra, the mythological Trojan prophetess, referencing her curse of making prophecies that were never believed.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Cassandra uses a distributed architecture where all nodes perform identical functions, eliminating single points of failure.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] The system employs configurable replication strategies to distribute data across clusters, providing redundancy and disaster recovery capabilities.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] The system is capable of linear scaling, which increases read and write throughput with the addition of new nodes, while maintaining continuous service.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Cassandra is categorized as an AP (Availability and Partition Tolerance) system, emphasizing availability and partition tolerance over consistency.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] While it offers tunable consistency levels for both read and write operations, its architecture makes it less suitable for use cases requiring strict consistency guarantees.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Additionally, Cassandra's compatibility with Hadoop and related tools allows for integration with existing big data processing workflows.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Eventual consistency is maintained using tombstones to manage reads, upserts, and deletes.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] The system's query capabilities have notable limitations.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Cassandra does not support advanced query patterns such as multi-table JOINs, ad hoc aggregations, or complex queries.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] These limitations stem from its distributed architecture, which optimizes for scalability and availability rather than complex query operations.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] As a wide-column store, Cassandra combines features of both key-value and tabular database systems.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] It implements a partitioned row store model with adjustable consistency levels.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] The following table compares Cassandra and relational database management systems (RDBMS).
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] A keyspace in Cassandra is analogous to a database in relational systems.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] It contains multiple tables and manages configuration information, including replication strategy and user-defined types (UDTs).
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Tables (formerly called column families prior to CQL 3) are containers for rows of data.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Each table has a name and configuration information for its stored data.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Tables may be created, dropped, or altered at run-time without blocking updates and queries.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Each row is identified by a primary key and contains columns.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] The first component of a table's primary key is the partition key; within a partition, rows are clustered by the remaining columns of the key.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Unlike traditional RDBMS tables, rows within the same table can have varying columns, providing a flexible structure.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] This flexibility distinguishes Cassandra from relational databases, as not all columns need to be specified for each row.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Other columns may be indexed separately from the primary key.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Cassandra uses a Log Structured Merge Tree (LSM tree) index to optimize write throughput, in contrast to the B-tree indexes used by most databases.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Every operation (create/update/delete) generates a new entry, with deletes handled via "tombstones".
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] While common in many databases, tombstones can cause performance degradation in delete-heavy workloads.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Cassandra Query Language (CQL) is the interface for accessing Cassandra, as an alternative to the traditional Structured Query Language (SQL).
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] CQL adds an abstraction layer that hides implementation details of this structure and provides native syntaxes for collections and other common encodings.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Language drivers are available for Java (JDBC), Python (DBAPI2), Node.JS (DataStax), Go (gocql), and C++.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] The key space in Cassandra is a namespace that defines data replication across nodes.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Therefore, replication is defined at the key space level.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Cassandra uses a peer-to-peer gossip protocol for cluster communication.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] The system uses vector clocks to track information currency and ignore outdated state data.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] This design eliminates single points of failure while maintaining cluster-wide consistency of operational knowledge.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Cassandra employs the Phi Accrual Failure Detector to manage node failures during cluster operation.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Through this system, each node independently assesses the availability of other nodes during gossip communication.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] When a node fails to respond, it is "convicted" and removed from write operations, though it can rejoin the cluster upon resuming heartbeat signals.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] To maintain data integrity during node outages, Cassandra uses a "hinted handoff" mechanism.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] When writing to an offline node, the coordinator node temporarily stores the write data as a "hint." Once the offline node returns to service, these hints are forwarded to restore data consistency.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Notably, Cassandra only permanently removes nodes through explicit administrative decommissioning or rebuilding, preventing temporary communication failures or restarts from triggering unnecessary data rebalancing.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Cassandra is a Java-based system that can be managed and monitored via Java Management Extensions (JMX).
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] The JMX-compliant *Nodetool* utility, for instance, can be used to manage a Cassandra cluster.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Nodetool also offers a number of commands to return Cassandra metrics pertaining to disk usage, latency, compaction, garbage collection, and more.
[src:cassandra-db/apache-cassandra] Since the release of Cassandra 2.0.2 in 2013, measures of several metrics are produced via the Dropwizard metrics framework, and may be queried via JMX using tools such as JConsole or passed to external monitoring systems via Dropwizard-compatible reporter plugins.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Apache Cassandra relies on a number of techniques from Amazon’s Dynamo distributed storage key-value system.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Cassandra primarily draws from the first two clustering components, while using a storage engine based on a Log Structured Merge Tree (LSM).
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Cassandra was designed this way to meet large-scale (PiB+) business-critical storage requirements.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Cassandra achieves horizontal scalability by partitioning all data stored in the system using a hash function.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Each partition is replicated to multiple physical nodes, often across failure domains such as racks and even datacenters.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] As every replica can independently accept mutations to every key that it owns, every key must be versioned.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Unlike in the original Dynamo paper where deterministic versions and vector clocks were used to reconcile concurrent updates to a key, Cassandra uses a simpler last-write-wins model where every mutation is timestamped (including deletes) and then the latest version of data is the "winning" value.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Formally speaking, Cassandra uses a Last-Write-Wins Element-Set conflict-free replicated data type for each CQL row, or LWW-Element-Set CRDT, to resolve conflicting mutations on replica sets.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Cassandra partitions data over storage nodes using a special form of hashing called consistent hashing.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] In naive data hashing, you typically allocate keys to buckets by taking a hash of the key modulo the number of buckets.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] For example, if you want to distribute data to 100 nodes using naive hashing you might assign every node to a bucket between 0 and 100, hash the input key modulo 100, and store the data on the associated bucket.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] In this naive scheme, however, adding a single node might invalidate almost all of the mappings.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Cassandra instead maps every node to one or more tokens on a continuous hash ring, and defines ownership by hashing a key onto the ring and then "walking" the ring in one direction, similar to the Chord algorithm.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] The main difference of consistent hashing to naive data hashing is that when the number of nodes (buckets) to hash into changes, consistent hashing only has to move a small fraction of the keys.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] You can see that in a Dynamo-like system, ranges of keys, also known as **token ranges**, map to the same physical set of nodes.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] In this example, all keys that fall in the token range excluding token 1 and including token 2 (grange(t1, t2]) are stored on nodes 2, 3 and 4.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Cassandra seeks to avoid token imbalance because uneven token ranges lead to uneven request load.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] For example, in the previous example there is no way to add a ninth token without causing imbalance; instead we would have to insert `8` tokens in the midpoints of the existing ranges.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] The Dynamo paper advocates for the use of "virtual nodes" to solve this imbalance problem.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Virtual nodes solve the problem by assigning multiple tokens in the token ring to each physical node.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] The mapping of **Tokens** to **Endpoints** gives rise to the **Token Map** where Cassandra keeps track of what ring positions map to which physical endpoints.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] When a node is decommissioned, it loses data roughly equally to other members of the ring, again keeping equal distribution of data across the cluster.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] If a node becomes unavailable, query load (especially token-aware query load), is evenly distributed across many other nodes.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Cluster-wide maintenance operations are often slowed.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] For example, as the number of tokens per node is increased, the number of discrete repair operations the cluster must do also increases.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Performance of operations that span token ranges could be affected.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Note that in Cassandra `2.x`, the only token allocation algorithm available was picking random tokens, which meant that to keep balance the default number of tokens per node had to be quite high, at `256`.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] This had the effect of coupling many physical endpoints together, increasing the risk of unavailability.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] That is why in `3.x +` a new deterministic token allocator was added which intelligently picks tokens such that the ring is optimally balanced while requiring a much lower number of tokens per physical node.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Cassandra replicates every partition of data to many nodes across the cluster to maintain high availability and durability.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] When a mutation occurs, the coordinator hashes the partition key to determine the token range the data belongs to and then replicates the mutation to the replicas of that data according to the `Replication Strategy`.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] All replication strategies have the notion of a **replication factor** (`RF`), which indicates to Cassandra how many copies of the partition should exist.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] For example with a `RF=3` keyspace, the data will be written to three distinct **replicas**.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Replicas are always chosen such that they are distinct physical nodes which is achieved by skipping virtual nodes if needed.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Replication strategies may also choose to skip nodes present in the same failure domain such as racks or datacenters so that Cassandra clusters can tolerate failures of whole racks and even datacenters of nodes.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Cassandra supports pluggable **replication strategies**, which determine which physical nodes act as replicas for a given token range.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Every keyspace of data has its own replication strategy.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] All production deployments should use the `NetworkTopologyStrategy` while the `SimpleStrategy` replication strategy is useful only for testing clusters where you do not yet know the datacenter layout of the cluster.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] `NetworkTopologyStrategy` requires a specified replication factor for each datacenter in the cluster.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Even if your cluster only uses a single datacenter, `NetworkTopologyStrategy` is recommended over `SimpleStrategy` to make it easier to add new physical or virtual datacenters to the cluster later, if required.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] In addition to allowing the replication factor to be specified individually by datacenter, `NetworkTopologyStrategy` also attempts to choose replicas within a datacenter from different racks as specified by the `Snitch`.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] If the number of racks is greater than or equal to the replication factor for the datacenter, each replica is guaranteed to be chosen from a different rack.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Otherwise, each rack will hold at least one replica, but some racks may hold more than one.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Note that this rack-aware behavior has some potentially surprising implications.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] For example, if there are not an even number of nodes in each rack, the data load on the smallest rack may be much higher.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Similarly, if a single node is bootstrapped into a brand new rack, it will be considered a replica for the entire ring.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] For this reason, many operators choose to configure all nodes in a single availability zone or similar failure domain as a single "rack".
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] `SimpleStrategy` allows a single integer `replication_factor` to be defined.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] This determines the number of nodes that should contain a copy of each row.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] For example, if `replication_factor` is 3, then three different nodes should store a copy of each row.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] `SimpleStrategy` treats all nodes identically, ignoring any configured datacenters or racks.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] To determine the replicas for a token range, Cassandra iterates through the tokens in the ring, starting with the token range of interest.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] For each token, it checks whether the owning node has been added to the set of replicas, and if it has not, it is added to the set.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] This process continues until `replication_factor` distinct nodes have been added to the set of replicas.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Transient replication is an experimental feature in Cassandra 4.0 not present in the original Dynamo paper.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] This feature allows configuration of a subset of replicas to replicate only data that hasn’t been incrementally repaired.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] This configuration decouples data redundancy from availability.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] For instance, if you have a keyspace replicated at RF=3, and alter it to RF=5 with two transient replicas, you go from tolerating one failed replica to tolerating two, without corresponding increase in storage usage.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Now, three nodes will replicate all the data for a given token range, and the other two will only replicate data that hasn’t been incrementally repaired.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] To use transient replication, first enable the option in `cassandra.yaml`.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Once enabled, both `SimpleStrategy` and `NetworkTopologyStrategy` can be configured to transiently replicate data.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Configure it by specifying replication factor as `<total_replicas>/<transient_replicas` Both `SimpleStrategy` and `NetworkTopologyStrategy` support configuring transient replication.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Transiently replicated keyspaces only support tables created with `read_repair` set to `NONE`; monotonic reads are not currently supported.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] You also can’t use `LWT`, logged batches, or counters in 4.0.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] You will possibly never be able to use materialized views with transiently replicated keyspaces and probably never be able to use secondary indices with them.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Transient replication is an experimental feature that is not ready for production use.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] The expected audience is experienced users of Cassandra capable of fully validating a deployment of their particular application.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] That means you have the experience to check that operations like reads, writes, decommission, remove, rebuild, repair, and replace all work with your queries, data, configuration, operational practices, and availability requirements.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Anticipated additional features in `4.next` are support for monotonic reads with transient replication, as well as LWT, logged batches, and counters.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Cassandra uses mutation timestamp versioning to guarantee eventual consistency of data.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Specifically all mutations that enter the system do so with a timestamp provided either from a client clock or, absent a client-provided timestamp, from the coordinator node’s clock.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Updates resolve according to the conflict resolution rule of last write wins.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Cassandra’s correctness does depend on these clocks, so make sure a proper time synchronization process is running such as NTP.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Cassandra applies separate mutation timestamps to every column of every row within a CQL partition.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Rows are guaranteed to be unique by primary key, and each column in a row resolves concurrent mutations according to last-write-wins conflict resolution.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] This means that updates to different primary keys within a partition can actually resolve without conflict!
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Furthermore the CQL collection types such as maps and sets use this same conflict-free mechanism, meaning that concurrent updates to maps and sets are guaranteed to resolve as well.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] As replicas in Cassandra can accept mutations independently, it is possible for some replicas to have newer data than others.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Cassandra has many best-effort techniques to drive convergence of replicas including `Replica read repair <read-repair>` in the read path and `Hinted handoff <hints>` in the write path.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] These techniques are only best-effort, however, and to guarantee eventual consistency Cassandra implements `anti-entropy repair <repair>` where replicas calculate hierarchical hash trees over their datasets called Merkle trees that can then be compared across replicas to identify mismatched data.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Like the original Dynamo paper Cassandra supports full repairs where replicas hash their entire dataset, create Merkle trees, send them to each other and sync any ranges that don’t match.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Unlike the original Dynamo paper, Cassandra also implements sub-range repair and incremental repair.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Sub-range repair allows Cassandra to increase the resolution of the hash trees (potentially down to the single partition level) by creating a larger number of trees that span only a portion of the data range.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Incremental repair allows Cassandra to only repair the partitions that have changed since the last repair.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Cassandra supports a per-operation tradeoff between consistency and availability through **Consistency Levels**.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Cassandra’s consistency levels are a version of Dynamo’s `R + W > N` consistency mechanism where operators could configure the number of nodes that must participate in reads (`R`) and writes (`W`) to be larger than the replication factor (`N`).
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] In Cassandra, you instead choose from a menu of common consistency levels which allow the operator to pick `R` and `W` behavior without knowing the replication factor.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Generally writes will be visible to subsequent reads when the read consistency level contains enough nodes to guarantee a quorum intersection with the write consistency level.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] A majority (n/2 + 1) of the replicas must respond.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] A majority of the replicas in the local datacenter (whichever datacenter the coordinator is in) must respond.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] A majority of the replicas in each datacenter must respond.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] In a multi-datacenter cluster, this also guarantees that read requests are not sent to replicas in a remote datacenter.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] A single replica may respond, or the coordinator may store a hint.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] If a hint is stored, the coordinator will later attempt to replay the hint and deliver the mutation to the replicas.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] This consistency level is only accepted for write operations.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Write operations **are always sent to all replicas**, regardless of consistency level.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] The consistency level simply controls how many responses the coordinator waits for before responding to the client.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] For read operations, the coordinator generally only issues read commands to enough replicas to satisfy the consistency level.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] The one exception to this is when speculative retry may issue a redundant read request to an extra replica if the original replicas have not responded within a specified time window.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] It is common to pick read and write consistency levels such that the replica sets overlap, resulting in all acknowledged writes being visible to subsequent reads.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] This is typically expressed in the same terms Dynamo does, in that `W + R > RF`, where `W` is the write consistency level, `R` is the read consistency level, and `RF` is the replication factor.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] For example, if `RF = 3`, a `QUORUM` request will require responses from at least `2/3` replicas.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] If `QUORUM` is used for both writes and reads, at least one of the replicas is guaranteed to participate in *both* the write and the read request, which in turn guarantees that the quorums will overlap and the write will be visible to the read.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] In a multi-datacenter environment, `LOCAL_QUORUM` can be used to provide a weaker but still useful guarantee: reads are guaranteed to see the latest write from within the same datacenter.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] This is often sufficient as clients homed to a single datacenter will read their own writes.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] If this type of strong consistency isn’t required, lower consistency levels like `LOCAL_ONE` or `ONE` may be used to improve throughput, latency, and availability.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] With replication spanning multiple datacenters, `LOCAL_ONE` is typically less available than `ONE` but is faster as a rule.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Indeed `ONE` will succeed if a single replica is available in any datacenter.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] The replication protocols and dataset partitioning rely on knowing which nodes are alive and dead in the cluster so that write and read operations can be optimally routed.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] In Cassandra liveness information is shared in a distributed fashion through a failure detection mechanism based on a gossip protocol.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Gossip is how Cassandra propagates basic cluster bootstrapping information such as endpoint membership and internode network protocol versions.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] In Cassandra’s gossip system, nodes exchange state information not only about themselves but also about other nodes they know about.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] This information is versioned with a vector clock of `(generation, version)` tuples, where the generation is a monotonic timestamp and version is a logical clock that increments roughly every second.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] These logical clocks allow Cassandra gossip to ignore old versions of cluster state just by inspecting the logical clocks presented with gossip messages.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Every node in the Cassandra cluster runs the gossip task independently and periodically.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Picks a random other node in the cluster to exchange gossip endpoint state with.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Gossips with a seed node if that didn’t happen in step 2.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] When an operator first bootstraps a Cassandra cluster, they designate certain nodes as seed nodes.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Any node can be a seed node, and the only difference between seed and non-seed nodes is that seed nodes are allowed to bootstrap into the ring without seeing any other seed nodes.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Furthermore, once a cluster is bootstrapped, seed nodes become hotspots for gossip due to step 4 above.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] As non-seed nodes must be able to contact at least one seed node in order to bootstrap into the cluster, it is common to include multiple seed nodes, often one for each rack or datacenter.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Seed nodes are often chosen using existing off-the-shelf service discovery mechanisms.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Currently, gossip also propagates token metadata and schema *version* information.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] This information forms the control plane for scheduling data movements and schema pulls.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] For example, if a node sees a mismatch in schema version in gossip state, it will schedule a schema sync task with the other nodes.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] As token information propagates via gossip it is also the control plane for teaching nodes which endpoints own what data.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Gossip forms the basis of ring membership, but the **failure detector** ultimately makes decisions about if nodes are `UP` or `DOWN`.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Every node in Cassandra runs a variant of the Phi Accrual Failure Detector, in which every node is constantly making an independent decision of if their peer nodes are available or not.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] This decision is primarily based on received heartbeat state.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] For example, if a node does not see an increasing heartbeat from a node for a certain amount of time, the failure detector "convicts" that node, at which point Cassandra will stop routing reads to it (writes will typically be written to hints).
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] If/when the node starts heartbeating again, Cassandra will try to reach out and connect, and if it can open communication channels it will mark that node as available.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Cassandra will never remove a node from gossip state without explicit instruction from an operator via a decommission operation or a new node bootstrapping with a `replace_address_first_boot` option.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] This choice is intentional to allow Cassandra nodes to temporarily fail without causing data to needlessly re-balance.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] This also helps to prevent simultaneous range movements, where multiple replicas of a token range are moving at the same time, which can violate monotonic consistency and can even cause data loss.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Cassandra scales-out to meet the requirements of growth in data size and request rates.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Scaling-out means adding additional nodes to the ring, and every additional node brings linear improvements in compute and storage.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] In contrast, scaling-up implies adding more capacity to the existing database nodes.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Cassandra is also capable of scale-up, and in certain environments it may be preferable depending on the deployment.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Cassandra gives operators the flexibility to choose either scale-out or scale-up.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] One key aspect of Dynamo that Cassandra follows is to attempt to run on commodity hardware, and many engineering choices are made under this assumption.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] For example, Cassandra assumes nodes can fail at any time, auto-tunes to make the best use of CPU and memory resources available and makes heavy use of advanced compression and caching techniques to get the most storage out of limited memory and storage capabilities.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Cassandra, like Dynamo, chooses not to provide cross-partition transactions that are common in SQL Relational Database Management Systems (RDBMS).
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] This both gives the programmer a simpler read and write API, and allows Cassandra to more easily scale horizontally since multi-partition transactions spanning multiple nodes are notoriously difficult to implement and typically very latent.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Instead, Cassandra chooses to offer fast, consistent, latency at any scale for single partition operations, allowing retrieval of entire partitions or only subsets of partitions based on primary key filters.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Furthermore, Cassandra does support single partition compare and swap functionality via the lightweight transaction CQL API.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Cassandra, in a slight departure from Dynamo, chooses a storage interface that is more sophisticated than "simple key-value" stores but significantly less complex than SQL relational data models.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Cassandra presents a wide-column store interface, where partitions of data contain multiple rows, each of which contains a flexible set of individually typed columns.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Every row is uniquely identified by the partition key and one or more clustering keys, and every row can have as many columns as needed.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] This allows users to flexibly add new columns to existing datasets as new requirements surface.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Schema changes involve only metadata changes and run fully concurrently with live workloads.
[src:cassandra-db/architecture-dynamo] Therefore, users can safely add columns to existing Cassandra databases while remaining confident that query performance will not degrade.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] A **gossip protocol** or **epidemic protocol** is a procedure or process of computer peer-to-peer communication that is based on the way epidemics spread.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] Some distributed systems use peer-to-peer gossip to ensure that data is disseminated to all members of a group.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] Some ad-hoc networks have no central registry and the only way to spread common data is to rely on each member to pass it along to their neighbors.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] The concept of *gossip communication* can be illustrated by the analogy of office workers spreading rumors.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] Let's say each hour the office workers congregate around the water cooler.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] Each employee pairs off with another, chosen at random, and shares the latest gossip.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] At the start of the day, Dave starts a new rumor: he comments to Bob that he believes that Charlie dyes his mustache.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] At the next meeting, Bob tells Alice, while Dave repeats the idea to Eve.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] After each water cooler rendezvous, the number of individuals who have heard the rumor roughly doubles (though this doesn't account for gossiping twice to the same person; perhaps Dave tries to tell the story to Frank, only to find that Frank already heard it from Alice).
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] Computer systems typically implement this type of protocol with a form of random "peer selection": with a given frequency, each machine picks another machine at random and shares any rumors.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] There are probably hundreds of variants of specific gossip-like protocols because each use-scenario is likely to be customized to the organization's specific needs.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] *Background data dissemination protocols* continuously gossip about information associated with the participating nodes.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] Typically, propagation latency isn't a concern, perhaps because the information in question changes slowly or there is no significant penalty for acting upon slightly stale data.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] Many protocols that predate the earliest use of the term "gossip" fall within this rather inclusive definition.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] For example, Internet routing protocols often use gossip-like information exchanges.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] A gossip substrate can be used to implement a standard routed network: nodes "gossip" about traditional point-to-point messages, effectively pushing traffic through the gossip layer.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] Bandwidth permitting, this implies that a gossip system can potentially support any classic protocol or implement any classical distributed service.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] However, such a broadly inclusive interpretation is rarely intended.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] More typically gossip protocols are those that specifically run in a regular, periodic, relatively lazy, symmetric and decentralized manner; the high degree of symmetry among nodes is particularly characteristic.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] Thus, while one could run a 2-phase commit protocol over a gossip substrate, doing so would be at odds with the spirit, if not the wording, of the definition.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] The term *convergently consistent* is sometimes used to describe protocols that achieve exponentially rapid spread of information.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] For this purpose, a protocol must propagate any new information to all nodes that will be affected by the information within time logarithmic in the size of the system (the "mixing time" must be logarithmic in system size).
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] Suppose that we want to find the object that most closely matches some search pattern, within a network of unknown size, but where the computers are linked to one another and where each machine is running a small *agent* program that implements a gossip protocol.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] If the messages might get large (for example, if many searches are active all at the same time), a size limit should be introduced.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] Also, searches should "age out" of the network.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] It follows that within logarithmic time in the size of the network (the number of agents), any new search string will have reached all agents.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] Within an additional delay of the same approximate length, every agent will learn where the best match can be found.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] In particular, the agent that started the search will have found the best match.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] For example, in a network with 25,000 machines, we can find the best match after about 30 rounds of gossip: 15 to spread the search string and 15 more to discover the best match.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] A gossip exchange could occur as often as once every tenth of a second without imposing undue load, hence this form of network search could search a big data center in about three seconds.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] In this scenario, searches might automatically age out of the network after, say, 10 seconds.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] By then, the initiator knows the answer and there is no point in further gossip about that search.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] Gossip protocols can be used to propagate information in a manner rather similar to the way that a viral infection spreads in a biological population.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] Indeed, the mathematics of epidemics are often used to model the mathematics of gossip communication.
[src:cassandra-db/gossip-protocol] The term *epidemic algorithm* is sometimes employed when describing a software system in which this kind of gossip-based information propagation is employed.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] A hash tree allows efficient and secure verification of the contents of a large data structure.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] A hash tree is a generalization of a hash list and a hash chain.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] Demonstrating that a leaf node is a part of a given binary hash tree requires computing a number of hashes proportional to the logarithm of the number of leaf nodes in the tree.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] Conversely, in a hash list, the number is proportional to the number of leaf nodes itself.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] A Merkle tree is therefore an efficient example of a cryptographic commitment scheme, in which the root of the tree is seen as a commitment and leaf nodes may be revealed and proven to be part of the original commitment.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] The concept of a hash tree is named after Ralph Merkle, who patented it in 1979.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] Hash trees can be used to verify any kind of data stored, handled and transferred in and between computers.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] They can help ensure that data blocks received from other peers in a peer-to-peer network are received undamaged and unaltered, and even to check that the other peers do not lie and send fake blocks.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] Suggestions have been made to use hash trees in trusted computing systems.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] A hash tree is a tree of hashes in which the leaves (i.e., leaf nodes, sometimes also called "leafs") are hashes of data blocks in, for instance, a file or set of files.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] Nodes farther up in the tree are the hashes of their respective children.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] For example, in the above picture *hash 0* is the result of hashing the concatenation of *hash 0-0* and *hash 0-1*.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] That is, *hash 0* = *hash*( *hash 0-0* + *hash 0-1* ) where "+" denotes concatenation.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] Most hash tree implementations are binary (two child nodes under each node) but they can just as well use many more child nodes under each node.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] Usually, a cryptographic hash function such as SHA-2 is used for the hashing.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] If the hash tree only needs to protect against unintentional damage, non-cryptographic checksums such as CRCs can be used.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] In the top of a hash tree there is a *top hash* (or *root hash* or *master hash*).
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] Before downloading a file on a P2P network, in most cases the top hash is acquired from a trusted source, for instance a friend or a web site that is known to have good recommendations of files to download.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] When the top hash is available, the hash tree can be received from any non-trusted source, like any peer in the P2P network.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] Then, the received hash tree is checked against the trusted top hash, and if the hash tree is damaged or fake, another hash tree from another source will be tried until the program finds one that matches the top hash.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] The main difference from a hash list is that one branch of the hash tree can be downloaded at a time and the integrity of each branch can be checked immediately, even though the whole tree is not available yet.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] For example, in the picture, the integrity of *data block L2* can be verified immediately if the tree already contains *hash 0-0* and *hash 1* by hashing the data block and iteratively combining the result with *hash 0-0* and then *hash 1* and finally comparing the result with the *top hash*.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] Similarly, the integrity of *data block L3* can be verified if the tree already has *hash 1-1* and *hash 0*.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] This can be an advantage since it is efficient to split files up in very small data blocks so that only small blocks have to be re-downloaded if they get damaged.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] If the hashed file is big, such a hash list or hash chain becomes fairly big.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] But if it is a tree, one small branch can be downloaded quickly, the integrity of the branch can be checked, and then the downloading of data blocks can start.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] The Merkle hash root does not indicate the tree depth, enabling a second-preimage attack in which an attacker creates a document other than the original that has the same Merkle hash root.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] For the example above, an attacker can create a new document containing two data blocks, where the first is *hash 0-0* + *hash 0-1*, and the second is *hash 1-0* + *hash 1-1*.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] One simple fix is defined in Certificate Transparency: when computing leaf node hashes, a 0x00 byte is prepended to the hash data, while 0x01 is prepended when computing internal node hashes.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] Limiting the hash tree size is a prerequisite of some formal security proofs, and helps in making some proofs tighter.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] Some implementations limit the tree depth using hash tree depth prefixes before hashes, so any extracted hash chain is defined to be valid only if the prefix decreases at each step and is still positive when the leaf is reached.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] The Tiger tree hash is a widely used form of hash tree.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] It uses a binary hash tree (two child nodes under each node), usually has a data block size of 1024 bytes and uses the Tiger hash.
[src:cassandra-db/merkle-tree] Tiger tree hashes are used in Gnutella, Gnutella2, and Direct Connect P2P file sharing protocols and in file sharing applications such as Phex, BearShare, LimeWire, Shareaza, DC++ and gtk-gnutella.
[src:cassandra-db/overview] Apache Cassandra is an open-source, distributed NoSQL database.
[src:cassandra-db/overview] It implements a partitioned wide-column storage model with eventually consistent semantics.
[src:cassandra-db/overview] Cassandra was initially designed at Facebook using a staged event-driven architecture (SEDA).
[src:cassandra-db/overview] This initial design implemented a combination of Amazon’s Dynamo distributed storage and replication techniques and Google’s Bigtable data and storage engine model.
[src:cassandra-db/overview] Dynamo and Bigtable were both developed to meet emerging requirements for scalable, reliable and highly available storage systems, but each had areas that could be improved.
[src:cassandra-db/overview] Apache Cassandra was designed as a best-in-class combination of both systems to meet emerging large scale, both in data footprint and query volume, storage requirements.
[src:cassandra-db/overview] As applications began to require full global replication and always available low-latency reads and writes, a new kind of database model was required to meet these new requirements.
[src:cassandra-db/overview] Relational database systems at that time struggled to meet the requirements.
[src:cassandra-db/overview] Cassandra provides the Cassandra Query Language (CQL), an SQL-like language, to create, modify, and delete database schema, as well as access data.
[src:cassandra-db/overview] Cassandra explicitly chooses not to implement operations that require cross-partition coordination as they are typically slow and hard to provide highly available global semantics.
[src:cassandra-db/overview] Apache Cassandra configuration settings are configured in the `cassandra.yaml` file that can be edited by hand or with the aid of configuration management tools.
[src:cassandra-db/overview] Some settings can be manipulated live using an online interface, but others require a restart of the database to take effect.
[src:cassandra-db/overview] Cassandra provides tools for managing a cluster.
[src:cassandra-db/overview] The `nodetool` command interacts with Cassandra’s live control interface, allowing runtime manipulation of many settings from `cassandra.yaml`.
[src:cassandra-db/overview] The `auditlogviewer` is used to view the audit logs.
[src:cassandra-db/overview] The `fqltool` is used to view, replay and compare full query logs.
[src:cassandra-db/overview] In addition, Cassandra supports out of the box atomic snapshot functionality, which presents a point in time (PIT) snapshot of Cassandra’s data for easy integration with many backup tools.
[src:cassandra-db/overview] Cassandra also supports incremental backups where data can be backed up as it is written.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] The Cassandra storage engine is optimized for high performance, write-oriented workloads.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] The architecture is based on Log Structured Merge (LSM) trees, which utilize an append-only approach instead of the traditional relational database design with B-trees.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] This creates a write path free of read lookups and bottlenecks.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] While the write path is highly optimized, it comes with tradeoffs in terms of read performance and write amplification.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] To enhance read operations, Cassandra uses Bloom filters when accessing data from stables.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Bloom filters are remarkably efficient, leading to generally well-balanced performance for both reads and writes.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Compaction is a necessary background activity required by the ‘merge’ phase of Log Structured Merge trees.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Compaction creates write amplification when several small SSTables on disk are read, merged, updates and deletes processed, and a new SSTable is re-written.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Every write of data in Cassandra is re-written multiple times, known as write amplification, and this adds background I/O to the database workload.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] The core storage engine consists of memtables for in-memory data and immutable SSTables (Sorted String Tables) on disk.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Data in SSTables is stored sorted to enable efficient merge sort during compaction.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Additionally, a write-ahead log (WAL), referred to as the commit log, ensures resiliency for crash and transaction recovery.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] When a write operation takes place, Cassandra records the data in a local append-only cassandra.apache.org/*/glossary.html#commit-log[commit log] on disk.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] This action provides configurable durability by logging every write made to a Cassandra node.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] If an unexpected shutdown occurs, the commit log provides permanent durable writes of the data.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] On startup, any mutations in the commit log will be applied to cassandra.apache.org/*/glossary.html#memtable[memtables].
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] All mutations are write-optimized on storage in commit log segments, reducing the number of seeks needed to write to disk.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Commit log segments are limited by the `commitlog_segment_size` option.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Once the defined size is reached, a new commit log segment is created.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Commit log segments can be archived, deleted, or recycled once all the data is flushed to SSTables.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Commit log segments are truncated when Cassandra has written data older than a certain point to the SSTables.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Running `nodetool drain` before stopping Cassandra will write everything in the memtables to SSTables and remove the need to sync with the commit logs on startup.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] When Cassandra accepts new write requests, it saves the data in two places: an in-memory write-back cache called a memtable and the CommitLog.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] The memtable buffers writes and allows serving reads without accessing the disk, while the CommitLog ensures durability by appending new mutations.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Typically, there is one active memtable per table, acting as a cache for data partitions that Cassandra accesses by key.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Depending on the `memtable_allocation_type`, memtables can be stored entirely on-heap or partially off-heap.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] If Cassandra crashes before flushing the memtable, it can restore acknowledged writes by replaying the commitLog.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] The memtable stores writes in sorted order until reaching a configurable limit.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] When the limit is reached, memtables are flushed onto disk and become immutable SSTables.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] When a triggering event occurs, the memtable is put in a queue that is flushed to disk.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Flushing writes the data to disk, in the memtable-sorted order.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] A partition index is also created on the disk that maps the tokens to a location on disk.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] The queue can be configured with either the `memtable_heap_space` or `memtable_offheap_space` setting in the `cassandra.yaml` file.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] If the data to be flushed exceeds the `memtable_cleanup_threshold`, Cassandra blocks writes until the next flush succeeds.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] You can manually flush a table using `nodetool flush` or `nodetool drain` (flushes memtables without listening for connections to other nodes).
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] To reduce the commit log replay time, the recommended best practice is to flush the memtable before you restart the nodes.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] If a node stops working, replaying the commit log restores writes to the memtable that were there before it stopped.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Data in the commit log is purged after its corresponding data in the memtable is flushed to an SSTable on disk.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] SSTables are the immutable data files that Cassandra uses for persisting data on disk.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] SSTables are immutable, and never written to again after the memtable is flushed.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Thus, a partition is typically stored across multiple SSTable files, as data is added or modified.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] The actual data, i.e. the contents of rows.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] The partition index file maps unique prefixes of decorated partition keys to data file locations, or, in the case of wide partitions indexed in the row index file, to locations in the row index file.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] The row index file only contains entries for partitions that contain more than one row and are bigger than one index block.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] For all such partitions, it stores a copy of the partition key, a partition header, and an index of row block separators, which map each row key into the first block where any content with equal or higher row key can be found.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] An index from partition keys to positions in the `Data.db` file.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] For wide partitions, this may also include an index to rows within a partition.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] A sampling of (by default) every 128th entry in the `Index.db` file.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] A Bloom Filter of the partition keys in the SSTable.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Metadata about the offsets and lengths of compression chunks in the `Data.db` file.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Stores metadata about the SSTable, including information about timestamps, tombstones, clustering keys, compaction, repair, compression, TTLs, and more.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] A plain text list of the component files for the SSTable.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Index information for Storage-Attached indexes.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Only present if SAI is enabled for the table.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Within the `Data.db` file, rows are organized by partition.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] These partitions are sorted in token order (i.e. by a hash of the partition key when the default partitioner, `Murmur3Partition`, is used).
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Within a partition, rows are stored in the order of their clustering keys.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] SSTables can be optionally compressed using block-based compression.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] As SSTables are flushed to disk from `memtables` or are streamed from other nodes, Cassandra triggers compactions which combine multiple SSTables into one.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Once the new SSTable has been written, the old SSTables can be removed.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Cassandra 5.0 introduced new SSTable formats BTI for Trie-indexed SSTables.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] Versions come from BtiFormat#BtiVersion.
[src:cassandra-db/storage-engine] For implementation docs see BtiFormat.md.
[src:cassandra-db/trunk-readme-asc] Apache Cassandra is a highly-scalable partitioned row store.
[src:cassandra-db/trunk-readme-asc] Rows are organized into tables with a required primary key.
[src:cassandra-db/trunk-readme-asc] Partitioning means that Cassandra can distribute your data across multiple machines in an application-transparent matter.
[src:cassandra-db/trunk-readme-asc] Cassandra will automatically repartition as machines are added and removed from the cluster.
[src:cassandra-db/trunk-readme-asc] Row store means that like relational databases, Cassandra organizes data by rows and columns.
[src:cassandra-db/trunk-readme-asc] The Cassandra Query Language (CQL) is a close relative of SQL.
[src:cassandra-db/trunk-readme-asc] For more information, see the Apache Cassandra web site.
[src:cassandra-db/trunk-readme-asc] Issues should be reported on The Cassandra Jira.
[src:cassandra-db/trunk-readme-asc] This short guide will walk you through getting a basic one node cluster up and running, and demonstrate some simple reads and writes.
[src:cassandra-db/trunk-readme-asc] For a more-complete guide, please see the Apache Cassandra website’s Getting Started Guide.
[src:cassandra-db/trunk-readme-asc] Running the startup script with the -f argument will cause Cassandra to remain in the foreground and log to standard out; it can be stopped with ctrl-C.
[src:cassandra-db/trunk-readme-asc] As the banner says, you can use 'help;' or '?' to see what CQL has to offer, and 'quit;' or 'exit;' when you’ve had enough fun.
[src:cassandra-db/trunk-readme-asc] If your session looks similar to what’s above, congrats, your single node cluster is operational!
[src:cassandra-db/trunk-readme-asc] For more on what commands are supported by CQL, see the CQL reference.
[src:cassandra-db/wide-column-store] A **wide-column store** (or **extensible record store**) is a type of NoSQL database.
[src:cassandra-db/wide-column-store] It uses tables, rows, and columns, but unlike a relational database, the names and format of the columns can vary from row to row in the same table.
[src:cassandra-db/wide-column-store] A wide-column store can be interpreted as a two-dimensional key–value store.
[src:cassandra-db/wide-column-store] Google's Bigtable is one of the prototypical examples of a wide-column store.
[src:cassandra-db/wide-column-store] Wide-column stores such as Bigtable and Apache Cassandra are not column stores in the original sense of the term, since their two-level structures do not use a columnar data layout.
[src:cassandra-db/wide-column-store] In genuine column stores, a columnar data layout is adopted such that each column is stored separately on disk.
[src:cassandra-db/wide-column-store] Wide-column stores do often support the notion of column families that are stored separately.
[src:cassandra-db/wide-column-store] However, each such column family typically contains multiple columns that are used together, similar to traditional relational database tables.
[src:cassandra-db/wide-column-store] Within a given column family, all data is stored in a row-by-row fashion, such that the columns for a given row are stored together, rather than each column being stored separately.
[src:cassandra-db/wide-column-store] Wide-column stores that support column families are also known as *column family databases*.
